{"cursor":"15474","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Conditional statement}} :For the rule of inference which is similar conceptually\nand in name see: [[Material implication (rule of inference)]]\n\nA 'material conditional' (also known as â'material implication'â, â'material\nconsequence'â, or simply âimplicationâ) is a logical connective often symbolized\nby a forward arrow âââ. A single statement formed from the connection of two,\nfor instance âpâqâ (called a conditional statement), is typically interpreted as\nâIf p, then qâ or âq if pâ. The material implication\nbetween two sentences p, q is typically symbolized as\n\n# p \\rightarrow q ; p \\supset q ; p \\Rightarrow\n# q (Although this symbol is often used for logical consequence (i.e.\n# logical implication) rather than for material implication.)\n\nAs placed within the material conditionals above, p is known as the [[antecedent\n(logic)|antecedent]], and q as the [[consequent]], of the conditional. One can\nalso use compounds as components, for example pq â (râs). There, the\ncompound pq (short for âp and qâ) is the antecedent, and the compound râs is the\nconsequent, of the larger conditional of which those compounds are components.\n\nImplication is one form of logical consequence. In an argument such as âFred is\nMikeâs brotherâs son. Therefore Fred is Mikeâs nephewâ the statement âFred is\nMikeâs nephew.â is a material consequence of âFred is Mikeâs brotherâs son,â but\nnot a formal consequence. This is because the validity of the argument depends\non the content of the premiss and conclusion (including the meanings of the\nwords âbrotherâ, âsonâ, and ânephewâ) rather than on the logical form or\nstructure of the argument. Logical consequence, Stanford Encyclopedia of\nPhilosophy\n\nIn classical logic, the compound pâq is equivalent to the negative compound: not\n(both p and not q). In particular, it is considered true if p is false, whether\nor not q is true. The only case in which the statement pâq is false is when p is\ntrue and q is false. In everyday English, saying âIt is false that\nif p then qâ is not often taken as flatly equivalent to saying âp\nis true and q is falseâ but, when used within classical logic, those\nphrasings are taken as logically equivalent. (Other senses of English âifâ¦thenâ¦â\nrequire other logical forms.)\n","linknr":285,"url":"Material_conditional","recorded":1362683974,"links":34,"instances":["mathematical_logic","logic","rule_of_inference","logic","mathematical_logic","linguistics","logic"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Logical connectives","Conditionals","Logical consequence"],"headings":["Definitions of the material conditional","Formal properties","Philosophical problems with material conditional","See also","Further reading","External links","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/c/f/2cf5c36392c6384e26d11ebb518c2699.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/b/b/8bb0129c5f2877fa4e9258890b1bdc76.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/5/7/f57e81295a72c855bfce85b8ff1a2d58.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/6/e766ce0de4bbe899d7ea2ebe40b3e0ee.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/e/4/fe447a0c9fd4cd67a968850b781d1595.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/5/b/25b6e0f1dbe92f822c43708e0614e3bf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/f/f/dff77b8d716d4e1e74a8963648905e9f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/0/5/9054bfc89c8340daeadaec7fb44e0724.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/3/e/83e37b7246fdfcb99b2754210ebeae27.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/6/e766ce0de4bbe899d7ea2ebe40b3e0ee.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/5/b/25b6e0f1dbe92f822c43708e0614e3bf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/a/e7a287aa16c350778029da351fc9d8cd.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/7/d/d7d6f937a0047807900b585146c68a36.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/2/3/c237b4009700ae4fcdbf082d57482924.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/6/5/f658b39cc748f89b3502b